    "Evaluation": {
      "text": "X-ray (perform before joint stressing)\nThere is a high association with avulsion fractures from insertion of UCL into proximal phalanx\nProximal phalanx volar subluxation and radial deviation suggests complete UCL rupture\nApply radial stress to the thumb with MCP in partial flexion\nCompare relative laxity to other thumb.\n>35 degrees of joint laxity or 15 degrees of releative laxity compared to other thumb is diagnostic of a complete UCL rupture\n[1]",
      "subsections": {
        "Stener_Lesion": {
          "text": "This phenomenon occurs when there is a UCL tear that results in entrapment of the adductor pollicis aponeurosis within the UCL. Clinically characterized by extensive laxity on stress testing of the thumb MCP.  Patients will require surgical repair\n[2]",
          "tables": []
        }
      },
      "tables": [],
      "links": []
    },
    "Stener_Lesion": {
      "text": "This phenomenon occurs when there is a UCL tear that results in entrapment of the adductor pollicis aponeurosis within the UCL. Clinically characterized by extensive laxity on stress testing of the thumb MCP.  Patients will require surgical repair\n[2]",
      "subsections": {},
